- introduction (what this is, who it's for, and the purpose)

[1] Specification. This is a digital diary of my recent learnings about Autism Spectrum Disorder (ASD). I want to catalogue what I have been learning to cement it in my mind.
[2] Audience. This publication is for parents and caregivers of autistic children. The depth of this article is probably not sufficient for professional reading, nor for autism service providers. For those simply interested in autism, this article will be interesting to read regarding the modern approach of treatment for autism. I hope to not include too much technical jargon and keep †his readable.
[3] Purpose. The purpose of this publication is to reduce the prevalance of misconceptions surrounding progress that can be made with ASD. The neuroaffirming movement is very recent, only having begun in the late 1990s, so many people still belive that autistic individuals are permenantly disabled in all aspects of life, however this is not true. Much progress can be expected to be made both behaviourally and cognitvely with the right approach and intervention.

– the history of Autism treatment
Around the early 1990s, a famous duo, Watson and Skinner, were publishing information regarding their beliefs of pysychology. Before their time, psychology was reduced to the physical structures and fucntions of the brain. Their approaches differed. Watson is known for his work in behavioural therapy, believing that thoughts were merely 'actions of the mind', and change was best acheived through observing mesurable actions (in order to be objective). This is the field of Behavioural Science. In contrast, Skinner took a different, more correct approach to psychotherapy. Skinner believed in the importance of thoughts in the 'mental space', and he made the distinction between mind and body. He worked on 'Operant Conditioning', affirming. ignoring, or punishing behaviour depending on its desiredness. Such a revelation led to 'Cognitive Revolution', where psychology progressed rapidly.
For autism, very little empathy was given to treatment at this time. Those who could not participate in society due to intellectual diability, lacking social skills, or fine-motor impairment were banished to asylums, and the current discourse surrounding them is negligently ignorant. In these asylums patients were lobotomised (leading to lack of empathy, reduced initiative, and decreased emotional expression); retarted^ patients were often abused, asaulted, and raped; and often fatal procedures such as Electro-Convulsive Therapy (ECT) were performed. Patients were treated as inhumane, and consequently this led to people being 'locked up' in asylums for thier whole lives. The goals of these institutions was not to reform, but to hide what society deemed as ugly.
In society for the more affluent, Applied Behavioural Analysis (ABA) Therapy was available a few decades later in the 1960s. This form of ABA was cruel, still forcing autistic people into the allistic (meaning non-autistic) profile. By trying to reduce harmless behaviours, this thearpy stripped austics people of self-expressionm idnetity

^retarded, meaning neurodevelopmentally delayed. Note this term is offensive in contemporary contexts.

